First Data Analysis Project

How can a Wellness Technology Company Play it Smart?

This capstone project will focus on a case study that deals with a company called Bellabeat. This will be my first project that I will examine to gain insight of the company as well as fulfill Google Data Anayltics Professional Certificate Program curriculum.

In this project I will use R studio to organize, clean, process, aggregate, and visualize different data sets that will comprise a further understanding of the company’s mission.

Background of Company

Bellabeat is a technology manufactured company that focuses on wellness and health products directed towards the women demographics. It’s a small comapny that has the potential to play a larger role in the global smart device market. Through the process of data analysis and understanding the data that their products and services output, the company believes they can expand their growth.

Questions to Ask

  1. What are some trends in smart device usage?
  2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy

Key Tasks

  1. Identify the business task- Focus on one of Bellabeat products, and analyze smart device data to gain insight into how consumers are using smart devices. Need high level recommendations for how these trends can inform Bellabeat’s marketing strategy. Identify potential opportunities for growth and recommendations for the Bellabeat marketing strategy improvement based on trends in smart device usage.
  2. Consider key stakeholders Deliverable Urška Sršen: Bellabeat’s co-founder and Chief Creative Officer Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeat’s co-founder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team. Bellabeat marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Bellabeat’s marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Bellabeat’’s mission and business goals — as well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Bellabeat achieve them.

Formatting Issues

There was some formatting issues when it came to time and date. The date/time needs to be converted and split into date and time.

# Intensities
Intensities$ActivityHour=as.POSIXct(Intensities$ActivityHour, format="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone())
Intensities$time <- format(Intensities$ActivityHour, format = "%H:%M:%S")
Intensities$date <- format(Intensities$ActivityHour, format = "%m/%d/%y")
# Activity
Activity$ActivityDate=as.POSIXct(Activity$ActivityDate, format="%m/%d/%Y", tz=Sys.timezone())
Activity$date <- format(Activity$ActivityDate, format = "%m/%d/%y")
# Sleep
Sleep$SleepDay=as.POSIXct(Sleep$SleepDay, format="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone())
Sleep$date <- format(Sleep$SleepDay, format = "%m/%d/%y")

What we learned from the Summary Statistics

  • In terms of Activity The mean of Sedentary Minutes is smaller than the median meaning the data might be skewed and half the participants are taking being more sediment than active. The data also shows that the average sedentary time is 991 minutes which is about 16 hours. This number needs to be reduced.

  • In terms of activity status, there is a clear indication that most of the participants are lightly active, this can be changed if they were to be more mindful of their activity status.

  • In terms of Calories, it seems like there is a huge gap between the minimum and maximum calorie intake. This shows at the minimum that someone will not consume any calories at zero, and on the other spectrum at the maximum caloric intake is at 4900. They are both very unhealthy numbers by not consuming anything at all, and over consumption.

  • In terms of Sleep, the mean or average of participants get about 7.21 hours of sleep, and they are in bed for about 7.71 hours in bed, which means that on average people sleep after being in bed for about 30 minutes, and they actually sleep.

  • In terms of Weight, the ratio between Weight and BMI index can be controlled and watched. According to the CDC research in the context of BMI, below 18.5 is underweight, 18.5-24.9 is Healthy, 25.0-29.9 is Overweight, and 30.0 and above is obese. It seems at a majority of the data the participants are healthy. Even at the minimum the BMI is at 21.45 which is still in the healthy range, and all the other participants from the 1st to 3rd quartile which is about 75% of the participants are healthy. There is obviously an outlier at the Max BMI at 47.54 because the spread of the 3rd quartile at 25.56 to the Max BMI has a high spread compared to the first 3 quartiles.

Visualization

Now we want to provide some context to the data, and provide visualizations to datsets to provide a visual narrative. To create some visualizations that make sense to the data, I will make various graphs thats will produce a scatterplot, and a bar graph to indicate the relationships between the various variables.

ggplot(data=Activity, aes(x=TotalSteps, y=Calories)) +
  geom_point(size=2, shape=21, fill="White")+ 
  geom_smooth()+ 
  labs(title= "Total Steps vs Calories")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data=Sleep, aes(x=TotalMinutesAsleep, y=TotalTimeInBed))+

  geom_smooth()+ 
  labs(title= "Total Minutes Asleep vs Total Time in Bed")

After making different charts and graphs to give some context for these datasets, we can give some insight to Bellabeat and their marketing team. In the first scatterplot, we can see that there is a postive correlation between Total Steps vs Calories. This makes sense because the more tatal steps means the more active you are and the more calories you will burn.

In the second scatterplot, we can see the relationship between the Total Time in Asleep vs Total Time Asleep shows a positive and linear corellation. To make a suggestion to the users, we can advise them to turn stop using all of their electronic devices at a certain time and keeping a stop limit when it is time for bedtime, to improve thier quality of sleep.

In the third bar graph, we can see the relationship between Time vs Total Intensity. There is a high level and peak activity at 5:00PM - 7:00PM and drastically lowers after 8:00PM. This also makes sense because the average workday ends at about 4-5PM so most people might be more active and workout, go to the gym, participate in any activity after their work hours. We can implement a system in the app when their is minimal activity to alert them of that status. This will reinforce and create a reminder for the users to be active. There should also be a reward and punish system, lets say that if they are lower than their lowest average then they should be warned, and if they pass their highest levels of activity they should receive an in app reward.

In the fourth scatterplot, we can see the realtionship between Weight vs BMI. In this instance it seems a majority of the users are maintaining a rational and healthy weigth and BMI index. However, to prevent future risks, we can implement a BMI index chart and body weight comparison in the app to see what ranges users fall in. We should also implement a color system where Green is healthy and Red is unhealthy, and users in the app will be have a private status of what their colors indicate.

Conclusion/ Final Thoghts

After undergoing our research, analyzing the context of the data, providing a visual narrative and context, we can finally give some suggestions to the Bellabeat marketing strategy team.

Target audience

Since Bellabeat’s approach and products are directed towards the female demographic, we can transition our focus towards that and implement proven strategies that have historically proven to work. A recent study by Bustle found that 81% of female millennials said social media was the best way for brands to reach them. Of those, around half said Facebook was the platform of choice, while the other half chose Instagram. Pinterest is also a strong platform of choice for marketing to a female demographic, with 78% of active Pinners welcoming branded content and messaging. In the Ernst and Young Groundbreakers, E&Y that women reinvest 90% of their income into their families and communities, compared to men, who reinvest only 30-40%. On top of that, 81% of millennials say they want companies to be good corporate citizens. Combined, both statistics present a compelling argument for brands to consider partnering with or championing a cause to create appealing marketing to a female demographic. Women dominate the influencer marketing space and accounted for 83.9% of all ad posts in 2017. In most cases, female influencers tend to attract an audience of other women, which makes them ideal channels for brands to use in marketing to a female demographic. Often, micro-influencers and even everyday brand customers can be used to build awareness of a brand, product, or services. Influencer marketing isn’t effective because of the size of an audience. It’s effective because influencer marketing by its nature fosters more trust and credibility than traditional advertising. In fact, 76% of individuals surveyed say that they’re more likely to trust content shared by “normal” people than content shared by brands. Hire women from different backgrounds, and at different levels, across your brand’s company.Hiring women opens your brand to the knowledge, background, and human layer that is essential to successful campaigns that you wouldn’t get from single gender teams.

Ideas for the Bellabeat app

From our Analysis we can see that collecting data on activty, sleep, stress, weight, among other things has kept the company to perform and maintain their framework to empower women on their health. In our findings through our analysis we can see that the total average steps per day is 7638, which is a little below the findings of the CDC research. According to CDC, taking 8000 steps per day was associated with 51% lower risk for all cause mortality or from all causes. Taking 12,000 steps per day was associated with 65% lower risk compared with taking 4000 steps. So we can encourage our users to take at least 8000 steps per day. If users want to track their sleep pattern they should take mindful steps to produce a healthier lifestyle. Setting a bed time system with the app will allow a more productive sleeping habit. If users want to improve or maintain their weight quality, they should include different informational forums and videos to better food choices, dietary information, and all around platform to better food consumption, training sessions, and calorie counting application. In terms of activity, the app should allow a system of activity tracking where users steps are counted and energy levels are also tracked. This will provide the users a notification if they are not where they should be in terms of activity levels.

Our main focus is to Bellebeat’s customers by providing them efficiency, affordability(price point), user protection and privacy, to ensure effectiveness and satisfaction of products, and accessibility to consumers whether it be product consumption or physical/ digital expenditures. If these factors are taken into consideration then the company can make some headway and dominate the market.
